1
00:00:00,453 --> 00:00:18,140
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:18,745 --> 00:00:31,716
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,658 --> 00:00:38,603
So I'm going to carry on with the Vikabodhi's book, In the Buddha's Words.

4
00:00:39,183 --> 00:00:43,847
This chapter is devoted to what he calls approaching the Dharma.

5
00:00:44,768 --> 00:00:48,212
It's basically our attitude to spiritual teachings.

6
00:00:48,698 --> 00:00:53,185
to those who teach spiritual teachings, the teachers, and so on.

7
00:00:53,204 --> 00:01:03,159
And how to, I don't know, be discriminative about spiritual practice and stuff.

8
00:01:05,763 --> 00:01:09,629
He's got certain headings, and so we'll sort of go through them, you know.

9
00:01:11,052 --> 00:01:12,415
So it's not a secret doctrine.

10
00:01:12,915 --> 00:01:14,638
So what he's teaching is not a secret doctrine.

11
00:01:15,579 --> 00:01:17,022
It's not a dogma.

12
00:01:17,221 --> 00:01:18,703
You don't need blind belief.

13
00:01:20,426 --> 00:01:23,670
It's the visible origin and passing away of suffering.

14
00:01:23,709 --> 00:01:28,415
It's something that you can actually perceive yourself.

15
00:01:28,456 --> 00:01:30,859
Investigate the teacher himself.

16
00:01:31,060 --> 00:01:31,820
Heaven forbid.

17
00:01:32,481 --> 00:01:34,144
Don't look at me like that.

18
00:01:34,164 --> 00:01:36,566
And steps towards realization of the path.

19
00:01:38,388 --> 00:01:40,731
I think that's his fullness of it.

20
00:01:41,093 --> 00:01:42,093
It is, yeah.

21
00:01:42,478 --> 00:01:45,643
So this evening, really, is just an introduction to this.

22
00:01:45,903 --> 00:01:52,974
And in his day, there were, you know, a choice of teachers.

23
00:01:53,534 --> 00:02:05,069
It was a time when the old Brahminical religion of the Rig Veda, which was based on control of the gods through various sacrifices.

24
00:02:06,512 --> 00:02:09,235
And there was, of course, the understanding of rebirth.

25
00:02:09,256 --> 00:02:11,979
But that, as I understand it, that was mainly...

26
00:02:12,382 --> 00:02:19,000
about power rather than whether one was good or not, depending on how you were born.

27
00:02:19,020 --> 00:02:26,560
So Brahmin was born from the head of Brahma and therefore was destined to join Brahma somewhere up there.

28
00:02:27,231 --> 00:02:36,665
But by the time of the Buddha, for some time, there'd been people who had really investigated the truth of all that.

29
00:02:37,266 --> 00:02:45,419
And that's the beginning of, in the Hindu tradition, of the Upanishads, which are really saying a lot of the things that the Buddha said.

30
00:02:47,782 --> 00:02:48,963
And there was...

31
00:02:49,525 --> 00:02:51,187
The Jains began there.

32
00:02:51,206 --> 00:02:55,212
The Jain leader, the Nigantha, was an elder, contemporary of the Buddha.

33
00:02:56,033 --> 00:02:56,715
And we...

34
00:02:57,252 --> 00:03:08,825
And it's thought that the ascetic practice that the Buddha did was either connected to him or under some of his disciples.

35
00:03:09,706 --> 00:03:13,592
That very fierce sort of ascetic practice.

36
00:03:14,713 --> 00:03:16,536
And of course there was the Buddha himself.

37
00:03:17,336 --> 00:03:23,985
And most of the teachers would have been within the tradition of the Brahmins.

38
00:03:24,168 --> 00:03:25,209
the Brahminical tradition.

39
00:03:26,230 --> 00:03:36,024
The interesting thing about Jainism and Buddhism is that they left that particular tradition entirely and formed their own scriptures from the words of the teacher.

40
00:03:36,824 --> 00:03:38,286
So it's a completely different line, you see.

41
00:03:42,231 --> 00:03:48,639
I wrote a sort of essay around the Eightfold Path, and I started off by...

42
00:03:49,818 --> 00:03:53,122
trying to distinguish five types of ideologues.

43
00:03:53,643 --> 00:03:55,645
So I thought I'd read it to you and then see what you think.

44
00:03:56,586 --> 00:04:00,572
So there seem to be five types of ideologues in the religious arena.

45
00:04:01,652 --> 00:04:02,794
So these are the five, you see.

46
00:04:02,814 --> 00:04:12,146
They are the fundamentalist, the relative fundamentalist, the relativist, the relativist universalist, and the universalist.

47
00:04:12,586 --> 00:04:14,830
I will now explain in great detail.

48
00:04:17,071 --> 00:04:21,137
The mountain is a good metaphor to illustrate these five different positions.

49
00:04:22,199 --> 00:04:26,524
Mountains come up in most spiritual literature.

50
00:04:26,966 --> 00:04:32,774
The interesting thing about mountain climbing is that when you're making the effort, when you're moving, all you can see is the ground ahead of you.

51
00:04:33,656 --> 00:04:38,423
And then finally when you get tired or you need a rest, you turn around and there's a view.

52
00:04:38,762 --> 00:04:40,925
You suddenly realize you're in a different place.

53
00:04:42,007 --> 00:04:45,372
And you never see the full 360 degrees until you get to the top.

54
00:04:46,062 --> 00:04:57,738
The Buddha talks about the Arahant who really doesn't see, it's only until we become fully liberated that we can really see things as in the noonday sun.

55
00:04:57,759 --> 00:05:02,906
So there's something about that end point which is quite awakening or enlightening.

56
00:05:04,769 --> 00:05:09,175
So the fundamentalist says that his is the only true mountain.

57
00:05:10,336 --> 00:05:14,161
You think you're climbing a mountain but actually you're descending into a pit.

58
00:05:16,014 --> 00:05:21,480
Whereas my mountain will take me to ultimate happiness, yours will take you to utter perdition.

59
00:05:23,023 --> 00:05:24,204
I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

60
00:05:24,444 --> 00:05:24,966
Utterly wrong.

61
00:05:25,305 --> 00:05:27,307
I mean, that's your fundamentalist, isn't it?

62
00:05:29,110 --> 00:05:31,593
Just basically, what can you say?

63
00:05:33,254 --> 00:05:36,079
The relative fundamentalist has respect for the traditions.

64
00:05:36,139 --> 00:05:37,641
Yes, indeed, they're all mountains.

65
00:05:38,281 --> 00:05:39,403
But my mountain is bigger.

66
00:05:40,423 --> 00:05:40,504
See?

67
00:05:41,411 --> 00:05:46,899
Whereas mine will reach the ultimate goal, yours will stop short, and at some time you'll have to cross over.

68
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:50,865
Everyone is right, but I'm more right than everybody else.

69
00:05:52,889 --> 00:05:59,699
So it's a sort of compassion for other people's parts, but ultimately, you know, this is the right one.

70
00:06:00,420 --> 00:06:06,930
It's funny because when I was in India once, I went to this Tibetan doctor, as I've been

71
00:06:07,045 --> 00:06:09,107
coals or something.

72
00:06:09,166 --> 00:06:14,954
He actually said to me in so many words, look, you're a Theravada.

73
00:06:14,973 --> 00:06:16,134
They've got it all wrong.

74
00:06:16,175 --> 00:06:17,916
What you want to join is the Mahayana.

75
00:06:19,338 --> 00:06:22,180
I was taken aback by it actually.

76
00:06:22,201 --> 00:06:24,002
Just the Hinayana, the lower path.

77
00:06:24,283 --> 00:06:33,473
These days they tend to refer to the two types of Buddhist traditions as the northern and the southern path.

78
00:06:34,435 --> 00:06:35,735
Northern and the southern Buddhisms.

79
00:06:37,994 --> 00:06:43,663
The relativist, acknowledging his ignorance of other religions, declares all mountains to be equal but different.

80
00:06:43,682 --> 00:06:49,392
They lead to their own idea of what is the ultimate good is, and there's no way of telling which is more true.

81
00:06:50,314 --> 00:06:51,896
Everyone is right but different.

82
00:06:52,377 --> 00:06:54,300
You take your pick and you guess what you choose.

83
00:06:54,360 --> 00:07:04,557
There's a sort of post-modernist view that, you know, you live in your own reality, and if you think you've achieved great happiness, then that's it, you know.

84
00:07:07,170 --> 00:07:17,865
The relative universalist argues that once we look below the surface of culture and words, we find that all religions are actually on the same, the very same mountain, all going up the same place.

85
00:07:18,365 --> 00:07:20,449
But that each path is distinct and separate.

86
00:07:21,069 --> 00:07:24,514
And we're all going in our own religious and cultural way to the same place.

87
00:07:24,954 --> 00:07:27,920
Everyone is different but right, and we all end up in the same place.

88
00:07:28,841 --> 00:07:33,346
I think probably a lot of people sort of kowtow to that one, I think.

89
00:07:34,389 --> 00:07:38,774
And then finally there's the universalist who takes this position a step further.

90
00:07:39,536 --> 00:07:47,764
So espying that indeed beneath the paraphernalia of rites, rituals, customs and culture there are three paths.

91
00:07:47,925 --> 00:07:50,588
The way of knowledge, the way of love and the way of action.

92
00:07:51,428 --> 00:08:03,283
And that is why many of the actual spiritual practices such as compassionate service, repetitive prayer, mantra, yoga and indeed vipassana can be practiced by people of different religious persuasions.

93
00:08:05,625 --> 00:08:11,413
These three paths are intertwined within the individual according to their temperament, all leading to the same place.

94
00:08:12,276 --> 00:08:16,240
The outer form is simply a metaphor for this deeper truth.

95
00:08:16,261 --> 00:08:24,353
And indeed, a Buddhist universalist may go so far as to say that even those who disavow all spirituality are also on the spiritual path.

96
00:08:25,194 --> 00:08:32,245
Eventually they will bump into the truth, everyone is actually on the same path and heading for the same destination.

97
00:08:32,264 --> 00:08:34,467
The ultimate universalist.

98
00:08:35,831 --> 00:08:39,456
I don't think you'll find Bhikkhu Bodhi particularly attracted to that one.

99
00:08:43,181 --> 00:08:50,910
It's interesting because Hinduism knows these three paths quite clearly as Jnana Yoga, Bhakti Yoga and Karma Yoga.

100
00:08:50,931 --> 00:08:56,337
The path of understanding somebody like Ramana Maharshi.

101
00:08:56,878 --> 00:08:59,741
You've heard of him?

102
00:08:59,761 --> 00:09:01,904
Nisigarata Maharaj, one of my favourites.

103
00:09:02,205 --> 00:09:03,206
Do you know him?

104
00:09:03,225 --> 00:09:04,427
Yeah, do you know him?

105
00:09:04,447 --> 00:09:04,587
Yeah.

106
00:09:04,607 --> 00:09:04,707
Yeah.

107
00:09:05,701 --> 00:09:06,721
Bhakti.

108
00:09:06,802 --> 00:09:09,524
Who was the great Bhakti Guru?

109
00:09:10,446 --> 00:09:10,765
Mother.

110
00:09:11,047 --> 00:09:12,447
He was into the Great Mother.

111
00:09:15,030 --> 00:09:15,631
Was that, was it?

112
00:09:16,472 --> 00:09:16,692
Yeah.

113
00:09:17,293 --> 00:09:18,153
There are a few like that.

114
00:09:18,835 --> 00:09:19,936
Just through love, really.

115
00:09:20,917 --> 00:09:22,298
Through the heart, you see.

116
00:09:22,339 --> 00:09:26,023
The connection to the ultimate through the heart, rather than through understanding.

117
00:09:28,426 --> 00:09:28,885
That's right.

118
00:09:28,926 --> 00:09:29,586
Hare Krishna.

119
00:09:29,667 --> 00:09:30,268
Yeah, that's right.

120
00:09:31,067 --> 00:09:33,530
And then there's the path of action, which is

121
00:09:34,134 --> 00:09:36,879
compassionate engagement in the world.

122
00:09:40,264 --> 00:09:59,352
It's interesting because, I don't know, it's just my own take on things, but of the three world, the ones that you can call really world religions, the ones that have transcended national boundaries in a real way, like are Christianity, Buddhism and Islam.

123
00:10:00,053 --> 00:10:02,116
And each have a particular bent, don't they?

124
00:10:02,552 --> 00:10:08,659
Buddhism is definitely the path of discrimination leading to the path of compassion.

125
00:10:12,203 --> 00:10:14,046
Christianity turns that around, doesn't it?

126
00:10:14,066 --> 00:10:17,769
The path of compassion leading to understanding.

127
00:10:18,471 --> 00:10:27,941
And Islam is the will, you see, the will of the Dharma, the will of surrendering to the truth.

128
00:10:30,924 --> 00:10:31,985
You've got these three

129
00:10:32,945 --> 00:10:40,434
So the will, I mean, that's action, giving oneself.

130
00:10:40,455 --> 00:10:48,745
So it's a case really of being aware of our position and not taking it too seriously.

131
00:10:49,287 --> 00:10:58,600
And when we approach the Buddha's teachings, his is always one of investigating it.

132
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:00,942
And we'll go into that more deeply later.

133
00:11:01,631 --> 00:11:03,934
how he doesn't want us to believe anything.

134
00:11:05,197 --> 00:11:14,408
That would be, in a sense it would make, it would distort the investigation of the truth if you come from a position of belief.

135
00:11:16,370 --> 00:11:29,749
The liberation in Buddhist terms has to be through something that we have explored and experienced directly for ourselves.

136
00:11:30,217 --> 00:11:41,072
And the problem is that if you approach something with a particular view or prejudice, belief, then that's what you'll experience.

137
00:11:42,553 --> 00:11:46,018
And that's where the mistakes can be made.

138
00:11:46,038 --> 00:11:57,373
So if you have an idea that nibbana is some sort of blissed out state, an emotional blissed out state, something like that, a mental state of being blissed out,

139
00:11:57,995 --> 00:12:03,222
then in your meditation if you get a blissful moment you'll think, oh that's Nibbana.

140
00:12:03,243 --> 00:12:05,886
But it ain't.

141
00:12:05,907 --> 00:12:11,235
So there's a, I always forget her name, but there's a woman who had this terrible stroke.

142
00:12:12,398 --> 00:12:17,365
She's fairly famous and she's written a book on it and how she overcame it completely it seems.

143
00:12:18,025 --> 00:12:25,538
And the right brain shut down and because the left brain was the only part working it

144
00:12:25,687 --> 00:12:28,769
She was just in this total euphoria all the time.

145
00:12:30,751 --> 00:12:33,875
And she expresses this as Nibbāna.

146
00:12:34,557 --> 00:12:35,236
See, this is the point.

147
00:12:35,977 --> 00:12:40,763
So that's one way to get Nibbāna is to have a stroke so you can get rid of your right brain.

148
00:12:42,024 --> 00:12:45,427
It's sort of a strange thing, you know.

149
00:12:45,447 --> 00:12:45,668
Left brain.

150
00:12:45,688 --> 00:12:47,370
Left brain, excuse me, left brain.

151
00:12:47,451 --> 00:12:49,032
I'm getting confused.

152
00:12:49,052 --> 00:12:50,614
It just shows you what I am.

153
00:12:52,871 --> 00:12:59,220
So there's a little, just an introduction into something that we can look more closely at.

154
00:12:59,620 --> 00:13:03,664
The way the Buddha asks us to approach the spiritual life, really.

155
00:13:06,428 --> 00:13:09,412
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

156
00:13:09,432 --> 00:13:14,038
May you be fully liberated from all suffering.

157
00:13:15,559 --> 00:13:19,605
Sooner rather than later.

